The duplicate reaction error suggests that there is some other  
problem with your mechanism.  Look at the cti file that ck2cti  
produces. Do the reaction specifications look right, and do all of  
the species have the correct elemental composition?  If that looks  
OK, then check the CTML file for the entries for these 2 reactions  
and their species.   Routine installReaction is in importCTML.cpp. If  
all else fails, put diagnostic print statements in, and recompile  
Cantera. But really I don't think that is where the problem is - I  
think it is something in the input file.  It might be the fact that  
you are using periods in your species names - that should be OK, but  
I don't think I've ever tried it.

Also, at the top of the cti file you can turn off mechanism  
validation, which will result in the duplicate reaction test being  
skipped.  I don't recommend this as a permanent fix, since there is a  
problem somewhere, but maybe it would let you get past this test and  
show you other errors that would pinpoint where the problem really  
is.  By the way, on a large mechanism like this one, turning off  
mechanism validation once you are sure the mechanism file is correct  
may significantly speed up the time required to read it in.


As far as the negative A coefficient error, the reaction number in  
the error message may be off by 1. Check the reaction before and  
after the number in the message.  Also, check the CTML file.  This  
error should only happen if an A value is really zero or negative. A  
large postive A coefficient should be no problem.


Dave
